{
  "text": "Adipose tissue stores energy as triacylglycerols (TGs) in lipid droplets formed through lipogenesis, and fatty acids (FAs) are released from these stored TGs via lipolysis. Both processes are reportedly elevated in insulin-resistant individuals with obesity compared to insulin-sensitive individuals with obesity [CITATION_1] . The cycle of lipid synthesis and degradation is required for the formation of diacylglycerols (DAGs) and free fatty acids (FFAs), which acts as regulatory ligands of nuclear receptors [CITATION_2] . Elevated formation of FFAs and DAGs due to increased lipolysis in adipose tissue, may contribute to impaired intracellular insulin signaling, i.e., insulin resistance [CITATION_3] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "24430304",
